<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2017-12-14T21:14:12-07:00</updated>
<published>2017-12-14T21:14:12-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16823&amp;p=210136#p210136</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16823&amp;p=210136#p210136"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: &quot;Ghostbusters!&quot; PCM little help needed]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=16823&amp;p=210136#p210136"><![CDATA[
DPCM means &quot;differential pulse code modulation&quot; because it stores the <em>difference</em> between one sample and the next. Sometimes it's referred to as &quot;delta pulse code modulation&quot; using a Greek letter Δ that often means difference between adjacent values in a sequence. In the NES scene, unqualified DPCM has a very specific meaning: the format accepted by the <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/APU_DMC" class="postlink">APU's waveform playback unit</a> at $4010-$4013, a 1-bit little-endian DPCM with a 64-step range.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Dec 14, 2017 9:14 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
